[2026-07-07] Android build fix â€” moved Gradle/Android redirected build output
  What happened: `flutter build apk --release` failed inside
    `:shared_preferences_android:mergeReleaseResources` because Windows reported
    `build/shared_preferences_android/.../multi-v2` as corrupted/unreadable.
    The stale `build/` tree could be listed at the parent level but not fully
    enumerated or deleted, so standard clean-up could not recover it.
  What changed:
    - android/build.gradle.kts: changed the repo-level redirected Android build
      output from `../../build` to `../../build_android`, forcing Gradle to use
      a fresh workspace build tree instead of the corrupted one.
  Why: avoid the broken Windows directory state without touching app/runtime code.
  Follow-up:
    - The first escalated release-build retry got past the unreadable
      `shared_preferences_android` resource folder, but then failed in Kotlin's
      incremental cache layer because plugin sources live on `C:` (Pub cache)
      while the project lives on `D:`. Kotlin tried to relativize files across
      different drive roots and crashed while closing caches for
      `shared_preferences_android` and `url_launcher_android`.
    - android/gradle.properties: added `kotlin.incremental=false` to disable
      that cross-drive incremental cache path on Windows.
    - With the temporary `build_android` redirect in place, Gradle produced a
      valid APK at `build_android/app/outputs/flutter-apk/app-release.apk`, but
      `flutter build` still exited non-zero because the Flutter tool only looks
      for the final artifact under the default `build/` path.
  Final fix:
    - Restored android/build.gradle.kts to the default redirected output path
      (`../build`) once the bad tree was out of the way.
    - Windows shell rename succeeded where deletion did not:
      `build` â†’ `build_bad` (quarantines the corrupted old tree so Flutter can
      recreate a fresh default `build/` directory).
    - Removed the temporary `build_android/` workaround folder after the final
      successful build.
  Result / verification (GREEN):
    - `flutter build apk --release` â†’ **SUCCESS**
    - Output: `build/app/outputs/flutter-apk/app-release.apk` (58.6 MB,
      2026-07-07 19:29 local time).
  Follow-up:
    - `build_bad/` is the old corrupted folder. It is no longer used, but if
      Windows later refuses to remove it, run a disk check / filesystem repair
      on that drive before deleting it.

